<DOC><DOCNO> AP880725-0132 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1647EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan-Floods     07-25 0171</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Floods,0177</SECOND><HEAD>Storms Kill 116 in Pakistan</HEAD><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Monsoon rains and lighting killed 116people in the past two weeks, including 33 members of one family,and destroyed thousands of homes, a government official said Monday.   More than a foot of rain caused flooding that inundated 7,000homes in the eastern province of Punjab, according to MohammadArshad, flood relief commissioner.   He said 1,000 villages along the Jhelum and Chinab rivers innorthern Kashmir province were flooded and more than 100,000 acresof land are under water, with cotton and rice crops the hardest hit.   Lightning started a fire that killed 36 people, 33 of them fromthe same family, and consumed eight homes in northeastern Pakistan,according to Pakistani television.   The storms also were blamed for one of the worst bus accidentsin Pakistan this year. A bus was swept into a shallow ravineThursday about 21 miles southeast of Islamabad, killing 70 people,police said.   Witnesses said panicked passengers jumped into the water anddrowned.</TEXT></DOC>